<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="OLL01" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Charles</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Ollier</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1788-05-04"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> </placeName></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1859-06-05"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">publisher</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">writer</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">editor</occupation><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Most likely this refers to Charles Ollier (1788–1859), publisher, writer, and editor. Charles
    had a younger brother named James who was in business with him and a J Ollier is mentioned in 1822 but there is no further attempt to differentiate Olliers,
    which suggests that the J Ollier entry is a single contrastive entry and that the others refer to Charles. </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> See Mary Shelley's <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Journal</title> - for 10, 11.1817 'Papa calls and Mr Ollier.' Almost certainly Charles
    Ollier to whom <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Frankenstein</title> had been submitted but who had turned it down, see p. 183, and p.
    174, n4. One of Shelley's political pamphlets had been accepted for publication by Ollier (p.
    166, n. 6) and Ollier published more by Shelley. It is not possible to be certain that Godwin
    consistently refers to Charles.  The two pieces of
    correspondence that survive in the Abinger collection, MS. Abinger c. 14, fols. 7-8: 25 Apr. 1831 and MS. Abinger c. 20, fols. 45-6:  6 July 1831 are from Charles Ollier (and are with reference to a
    contract for his latest novel) or to him (concerning the reprinting of <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Caleb Williams</title> and <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">St Leon</title>), 
    so it seems to be with Charles that most business was conducted.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">There is extensive correspondence between Ollier and Godwin and the Shelleys, much of which was listed in the 
    sale catalogue of Puttick and Simpson in 1877 and 1878, and most of which is now held in either the Pierpoint Morgan Library or the Pforzheimer Collection.</p>
    

